I was baffled by this problem as well. Here's what I wanted to do:

```python
def decorate_a_func(path):
    def _decorate(func, *args, **kwargs):
        baz = kwargs.get('baz')   # This didn't work as expected
        if baz:
            pass
        return func(*args, *kwargs)
    return decorator(_decorate)

@decorate_a_func(path=PATH)
def do_a_thing(foo, bar, baz):
    pass

do_a_thing(
    foo=123,
    bar=456,
    baz=True,
)

```

At the highlighted line above, kwargs was empty, and args was equal to (123, 456, True)

One solution is to do the following:

```python
baz = args[2]
```

This is probably fine if you don't mind the decorator being tightly coupled with the function(s) that it decorates, since now the decorator depends on that argument always being in the third position. That doesn't seem very ideal to me.

Alternatively, you can use inspect to build a dictionary of named arguments:

```python
import inspect
def decorate_a_func(path):
    def _decorate(func, *args, **kwargs):
        func_spec = inspect.getargspec(func)
        named_args = dict(zip(func_spec.args, args))
        baz = named_args.get('baz')
        if baz:
            pass
        return func(*args, *kwargs)
    return decorator(_decorate)
```

That works as expected, but seems like overkill. 

Is there a better solution to this scenario?

And here's that example. Note that when using child injectors, singleton scoped objects are singleton across all injectors.

```python
from injector import Injector, Module, singleton


class DB(object):
    def __init__(self, name):
        self.name = name

    def __repr__(self):
        return '<DB(%s) object at 0x%x>' % (repr(self.name), id(self))


class Issuer(object):
    def __init__(self, db:DB):
        print('issuer db', db)


def app_module(binder):
    binder.bind(Issuer)


class DbModule(Module):
    def __init__(self, name):
        self.name = name

    def configure(self, binder):
        binder.bind(DB, to=DB(self.name))


injector = Injector(app_module, auto_bind=False, use_annotations=True)


microsoft = injector.create_child_injector(DbModule("Microsoft"), auto_bind=False, use_annotations=True)
print(microsoft.get(Issuer))
print(microsoft.get(Issuer))
ibm = injector.create_child_injector(DbModule("IBM"), auto_bind=False, use_annotations=True)
print(ibm.get(Issuer))
print(ibm.get(Issuer))
```

I think this is directly related to #52, though it wasn't clear at the time why that one was failing.

The problem is that `SingletonScope` is bound to the root `Injector`. The child injector looks up the `@singleton` binding, which resolves to the instance bound to the root injector.

This definitely should not be the case. Here's the equivalent code in Guice, which does what you would expect:

```java
Injector injector = Guice.createInjector(binder -> binder.bind(A.class));
Injector childa = injector.createChildInjector(binder -> binder.bind(B.class));
Injector childb = injector.createChildInjector(binder -> binder.bind(B.class));

assertThat(injector.getInstance(A.class)).isSameAs(injector.getInstance(A.class));
assertThat(childa.getInstance(A.class)).isSameAs(injector.getInstance(A.class));
assertThat(childa.getInstance(A.class)).isSameAs(childb.getInstance(A.class));
assertThat(childa.getInstance(B.class)).isNotSameAs(childb.getInstance(B.class));
assertThat(childa.getInstance(B.class)).isSameAs(childa.getInstance(B.class));
 ```

If you had patching Hypothesis to make this work in mind I'd recommend against it for now. The runner loop is some of the oldest and hairiest code in the codebase and has been patched rather than refactored about 10 too many times. Sorting it out so it's less of a nightmare is on my TODO list and it will probably happen in the not too distant future, but I think trying to patch this in right now will just make it worse.

Could something like the following work for you instead?

```python
@given(str)
@runinloop
def test_foo(self, x):
        # here we expect the fail, but it never happens
        r = yield from aiohttp.request(x, 'http://localhost')
        assert r.status == 200, 'yay!'```

This will move your runinloop call to inside the bit that Hypothesis has access to, so it can invoke it as if it were just a normal function.

